AWS: EC2 is assigned an IAM Role. AWS Security Token Service provides temporary credentials. Permissions are defined in AWS Identity and Access Management policies and enforced by services like S3/DynamoDB.

Azure: VM is assigned a Managed Identity. Microsoft Entra ID issues an access token. Permissions are defined via Azure Role-Based Access Control and enforced by services like Blob Storage.
----------------------------------

1. Identity attached

AWS → IAM Role attached to EC2
Azure → Managed Identity enabled on VM

----------------------------------

2. AWS → AWS Security Token Service gives temporary credentials (Access key + Secret + Token)

Azure → Microsoft Entra ID gives OAuth access token (JWT)

Better way to say:

“STS and Entra ID both act as token/credential issuers”

----------------------------------

3. “IAM access vs RBAC permission”
AWS → IAM policies (JSON-based permissions)
Azure → RBAC roles

Important:

IAM ≠ just identity, it also includes permission system

----------------------------------

4. Where permission is validated

App → Service API call → Service checks permission → Allow/Deny

S3 checks IAM policy
Blob checks RBAC role

Ultra-Simple Version (remember this)
AWS:
EC2 → IAM Role → STS creds → S3 → IAM policy check

Azure:
VM → Managed Identity → Entra token → Blob → RBAC check